.TH "TEMPORAL.PLAINTIME.ADD" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.PlainTime.add \- Temporal.PlainTime.prototype.add()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]add()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R]
instances returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R] object
representing this time moved forward by a given duration (in a form
convertible by \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]), wrapping around the
clock if necessary.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
add(duration)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]duration\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instance
representing a duration to add to this time.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object using the same
algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R].
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R] object representing the time
specified by the original \f[CR]PlainTime\f[R], plus the duration.
Any units above \f[CR]hours\f[R] are ignored, and if the time goes past
midnight, it wraps around to the next day.
.PP
Adding a duration is equivalent to subtracting its negation.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Adding a duration
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.PlainTime.from(\(dq12:34:56\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] end = start.add({ hours: 1, minutes: 30 });
console.log(end.toString()); \f[I]// 14:04:56\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] end2 = start.add({ hours: \-1, minutes: \-30 });
console.log(end2.toString()); \f[I]// 11:04:56\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] distance = Temporal.PlainTime.from(\(dq00:00:00\(dq).until(\(dq01:23:45\(dq); \f[I]// 1h 23m 45s\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] end3 = start.add(distance);
console.log(end3.toString()); \f[I]// 13:58:41\f[R]
.EE
.SS Time wrapping
If the time goes past midnight, it wraps around to the next day:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.PlainTime.from(\(dq12:34:56\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] end = start.add({ hours: 12 });
console.log(end.toString()); \f[I]// 00:34:56\f[R]
.EE
